TITLE: Naive User Resolver Causing N+1 Database Queries in Go
DESCRIPTION: This Go function resolves the user for a todo by preparing and executing a separate SQL query for each user ID. It demonstrates the classic N+1 query problem where each nested field requires an individual database call, resulting in excessive query overhead. It depends on a `database/sql` connection and returns a user model or error.
SOURCE: https://github.com/99designs/gqlgen/blob/master/docs/content/reference/dataloaders.md#_snippet_1

LANGUAGE: go
CODE:
```
func (r *todoResolver) User(ctx context.Context, obj *model.Todo) (*model.User, error) {
	stmt, err := r.db.PrepareContext(ctx, "SELECT id, name FROM users WHERE id = ?")
	if err != nil {
		return nil, err
	}
	defer stmt.Close()

	rows, err := stmt.QueryContext(ctx, obj.UserID)
	if err != nil {
		return nil, err
	}
	defer rows.Close()

	if !rows.Next() {
		return nil, rows.Err()
	}

	var user model.User
	if err := rows.Scan(&user.ID, &user.Name); err != nil {
		return nil, err
	}
	return &user, nil
}
```

