TITLE: Implementing the @hasRole directive in Go server setup
DESCRIPTION: Shows how to assign the logic of the @hasRole directive within the GraphQL server configuration. The function checks the current user's role, blocking access if insufficient permissions, or passing control to the next resolver otherwise.
SOURCE: https://github.com/99designs/gqlgen/blob/master/docs/content/reference/directives.md#_snippet_2

LANGUAGE: Go
CODE:
```
func main() {
	c := Config{ Resolvers: &resolvers{} }
	c.Directives.HasRole = func(ctx context.Context, obj interface{}, next graphql.Resolver, role Role) (interface{}, error) {
		if !getCurrentUser(ctx).HasRole(role) {
			// block calling the next resolver
			return nil, fmt.Errorf("Access denied")
		}

		// or let it pass through
		return next(ctx)
	}

	srv := handler.New(NewExecutableSchema(c))
	srv.AddTransport(transport.POST{})

	http.Handle("/query", srv)
	log.Fatal(http.ListenAndServe(":8081", nil))
}
```

